## Functions

A **function** packages logic so it can be reused and composed. JavaScript offers several ways to define one.

```js
// Function declaration (hoisted)
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

// Function expression
const sub = function (a, b) {
  return a - b;
};

// Arrow function (concise, lexical this)
const mul = (a, b) => a * b;
```

### Parameters & return

Functions accept **parameters** and produce a value with `return`. Without an explicit return they yield `undefined`. Modern JS supports default, rest and destructured parameters.

```js
function greet(name = 'friend', ...rest) {
  return `Hello ${name}! (${rest.length} extras)`;
}
```

### Arrow vs regular functions

Arrow functions don't have their own `this`, `arguments`, or `prototype`. They're ideal for callbacks but unsuitable as methods or constructors.
